short_description: Generates an AML file from input model tables.
long_description: AMLGenerator generates an AML file from input model tables. The AML file is generated on the specified path location intended for Scoring use.

argument_clauses.name: Domain
argument_clauses.rDescription: The address of the Queen. The host parameter is the Aster Database Queen’s IP address or hostname.
argument_clauses.description: The address of the Queen. The host parameter is the Aster Database Queen’s IP address or hostname.

argument_clauses.name: Database
argument_clauses.rDescription: The name of the database where the input table is located.
argument_clauses.description: The name of the database where the input table is located.

argument_clauses.name: UserId
argument_clauses.rDescription: The Aster Database user name of the user running this function.
argument_clauses.description: The Aster Database user name of the user running this function.

argument_clauses.name: Password
argument_clauses.rDescription: The Aster Database password of the user.
argument_clauses.description: The Aster Database password of the user.

argument_clauses.name: SSLSettings
argument_clauses.rDescription: A string that includes all the SSL settings, except the password for the truststore.
argument_clauses.description: A string that includes all the SSL settings, except the password for the truststore.

argument_clauses.name: SSLTrustStorePassword
argument_clauses.rDescription: The password for the SSL truststore.
argument_clauses.description: The password for the SSL truststore.

argument_clauses.name: ModelType
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the function name for which this aml file will be used. For predictors, this represents the type of the model trained.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the function name for which this aml file will be used. For predictors, this represents the type of the model trained.

argument_clauses.name: RequestColNames
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the column names of the request to be scored. For a predictor, these column names typically match the columns names of the training data used to train the model.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the column names of the request to be scored. For a predictor, these column names typically match the columns names of the training data used to train the model.

argument_clauses.name: RequestColTypes
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the column types of the request to be scored. For a predictor, these column types typically match the columns types of the training data used to train the model.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the column types of the request to be scored. For a predictor, these column types typically match the columns types of the training data used to train the model.

argument_clauses.name: ModelTable
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the input model table representing input data for which aml file is to be generated. The argument clause accepts multiple input model tables. These tables could be either database tables or files installed on the database.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the input model table representing input data for which aml file is to be generated. The argument clause accepts multiple input model tables. These tables could be either database tables or files installed on the database.

argument_clauses.name: ModelTag
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the input model table tag for each input model table specified in model.table clause. Tags are supported for functions which accept multiple model tables and are used to distinguish the role of each model table in the context of the Aster Scoring SDK function.The number of entries must match the number of entries in the model.table clause.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the input model table tag for each input model table specified in ModelTable clause. Tags are supported for functions which accept multiple model tables and are used to distinguish the role of each model table in the context of the Aster Scoring SDK function.The number of entries must match the number of entries in the ModelTable clause.

argument_clauses.name: InstalledFile
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies whether the corresponding value in model.table is a file installed on database or a table on database. If model.table is a database table, set this to false (default) and if it is a file, set this to true. The number of entries must match the number of entries in the model.table clause.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies whether the corresponding value in ModelTable is a file installed on database or a table on database. If ModelTable is a database table, set this to false (default) and if it is a file, set this to true. The number of entries must match the number of entries in the ModelTable clause.

argument_clauses.name: AMLPrefix
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the name of the generated AML model file. Default value is “model”. The output file is stored with suffix “.aml”.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the name of the generated AML model file. Default value is “model”. The output file is stored with suffix “.aml”.

argument_clauses.name: OverwriteOutput
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies whether the output AML model file should be overwritten or not if already exists.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies whether the output AML model file should be overwritten or not if already exists.

argument_clauses.name: RequestArgName1
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the argument clause name for the function to be used in scoring. These clauses are the same as mentioned in the corresponding SQL-MapReduce function documentation, with some exceptions. The request.arg.name should start from 1 in a sequential manner. For example, the following sequence of clauses is acceptable: request.arg.name1, request.arg.name2, request.arg.name3. However, this sequence is not acceptable: request.arg.name1, request.arg.name2, request.arg.name4. The maximum value of n is 30. The values for corresponding arguments are provided in request.arg.val clause.
argument_clauses.description: Specifies the argument clause name for the function to be used in scoring. However, this sequence is not acceptable: RequestArgName1, RequestArgName2, RequestArgName4. The maximum value of n is 30. The values for corresponding arguments are provided in RequestArgVal clause.

argument_clauses.name: RequestArgVal1
argument_clauses.rDescription: Specifies the argument clause value for the function to be used in scoring. The value in this clause corresponds to the clause mentioned in request.arg.name for the same value of n. These clause values are the same as mentioned in the documentation for the corresponding SQL-MapReduce function. The request.arg.val should start from 1 in a sequential manner, and follows the same format as request.arg.name. The maximum value of n is 30.
